I'd still recomend taking a class though just for many other great reasons. Learning karate is one of the best things I've ever done and I wish I'd started earlier. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=neoangel>NeoAngel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/28/02 12:54:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1401.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  forms of techniques</span><hr size=1> OK, here is a newsflash - the forms of techniques are useless.  The way a move looks is not as important as how effective it is.  I'm not very flexible and I can't do high kicks. People laugh when they see me practice, and scream if I actually kick them.  How a move looks does not count - although psychology is good, all the forms teach you is balance.  If you learn the forms, but then practice combining forms you will learn the true ways to kick people around. For example, I only practice moves like the spinning-heel-kick or the crescent-kick as training for balance and flexibility - if I were to use them in a real fight I would die. You should remember this if you are drawing martial arts, lest ye be laughed at. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uascendedbob.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ascended Bob</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(2/28/02 1:24:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1401.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: forms of techniques</span><hr size=1> Why would you be laughed at for drawing martial arts cool and exaggerated. All things that apply in the real world do not have to apply in drawing. I would personally laugh at you if you can draw well and you prefer to draw in a comic/manga style and yet your drawings of a fight are seriously lacking dynamic. I don't think he wants to learn martial arts to learn to fight. At least thats not what he implied. He just wants to learn correct poses and such. For that I reccomend you save the tuition money and just buy a magazine. If however you do want to learn to further your self by all means go ahead and take a class. <p>My old aunts used to come up to me at weddings poking me in the side while cackling and saying, "You're next." <BR><BR>They stopped after I started doing the same thing to them at funerals. </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uswompz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Swompz</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.rpgicons.com/images/icons/bof4/pcs/ryu/victory.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(3/2/02 8:19:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1401.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.galeriadosexo.hpg.com.br/imagens/roach.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: forms of techniques</span><hr size=1> NeoAngel that isnt much of a news flash is it? Forms do teach ballance, but they are to enhance speed, muscle memory, ease of transition between moves ect.<br>
<br>
Taking a martial art would not be necisary, but can help to get a grasp of what a punch looks like when your fist is buried in somones stomach and they really need to lie down for a while, ur best bet would to buy some magazines like Combat, Martial arts international, Martial arts montly, u know.<br>
<br>
and study various moves, unless you want to make every character you draw to share the same moves as you do, u might want to add, judo for throws, learn about the chinese Iron shirt, iron palm techniques for those yough guys in ur stories. karate for open handed attacks or for devestating kicks. your list is endless, and of course u have Samurai and Ninjutsu &amp; Ninpo, hope this gives u some idea, do a search in a search engine for pictures aswell, good luck and mail me ur results <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>"Dance like my Roach Buddie, Roachie"

